Barren Land Analysis R Notebook

Setup

Install Tidyverse, load ggplot2

install.packages("tidyverse")

Visualizing the Problem Space

Run a test plot with a uniform distribution:

df <- expand.grid(x = 0:399, y = 0:599)
df$z <- runif(nrow(df))
ggplot(df, aes(x, y, fill = z)) + geom_raster()

Set the land to be default fertil (1) and an area of barren land (0):

df <- expand.grid(x = 0:399, y = 0:599)
df$z <- 1
# using test input {“0 292 399 307”}
df$z[df$x >= 0 & df$x <= 399 & df$y >= 292 & df$y <= 307] <- 0
ggplot(df, aes(x, y, fill = z)) + geom_raster()

I’m assuming the coordinates are inclusive for the barren land, but that may not be the case. Let’s validate the areas manually and compare with the sample output.

#area of top
(599-307) * 400
[1] 116800
#area of bottom
(292-0) * 400
[1] 116800

Inclusive it is! Moving on.

Let’s make a function that takes in a set of coordinate strings, and sets the barrenness of the land.

setBarren <- function(df, barren_lands, val=0){
  for (bString in barren_lands){
    b <- unlist(strsplit(bString,"[ ]")) #split on spaces
    b <- as.numeric(b)                   #convert string to numbers
    df$z[df$x >= b[1] & df$x <= b[3] & df$y >= b[2] & df$y <= b[4]] <- val
  }
  return(df)
}
# reset our grid
df <- expand.grid(x = 0:399, y = 0:599)
df$z <- 1
df <- setBarren(df, c("48 192 351 207", "48 392 351 407", "120 52 135 547", "260 52 275 547"))
ggplot(df, aes(x, y, fill = z)) + geom_raster()

Wait a second here …

I was reading the instructions as largest rectangle of fertile land. This is an incorrect reading of the initial instructions. We are simply looking for areas of contiguous space.

If I exclude the center patch (the obvious 2nd biggest area), then the largest congiguous area would look like this:

df2 <- df
df2 <- setBarren(df2, c("136 207 259 392"))
ggplot(df2, aes(x, y, fill = z)) + geom_raster()

And it’s area would be:

nrow(df2[df2$z==1,])
[1] 192608

Algorithm

Next up is the algorithm. There are actually two strategies I’d like to investigate. The first is if there are any R-specific tools available to do this. If so, I’d like to go down that route. If I don’t find anything in a reasonable amount of time then I’ll likely build a solution similar to Flood fill

R-specific tools

Flood fill

# z=0 is barren land
# z=1 is fertile land
# z=.25 is marked fertile land that we are currently counting
floodFill <- function(xCord, yCord) {
  zVal <- df[df$x==xCord & df$y==yCord,]$z
  if (is.na(zVal) | zVal == .75 | zVal == 0) { return() }
  if (zVal == 1) {
    df[df$x==xCord & df$y==yCord,]$z <<- .75
    # left
    if (xCord > 0) { floodFill(xCord-1, yCord) }
    # right
    if (xCord < 399) { floodFill(xCord+1, yCord) }
    # up
    if (yCord < 599) { floodFill(xCord, yCord+1) }
    # down
    if (yCord > 0) { floodFill(xCord, yCord-1) }
  }
}
floodFill(0,0)
ggplot(df, aes(x, y, fill = z)) + geom_raster()
